<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: Thu, 24 Mar 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: DEFRA news release 156/05, 24 Mar 2005 [edited]
<http://www.defra.gov.uk/news/2005/050324f.htm>

Brucella Investigation Following High Number of Test Failures
-------------------------------------------------
Defra has imposed precautionary movement restrictions on a farm in
Derbyshire following a high number of brucella test failures.
A number of reactors have been identified in the dairy herd following
a herd blood test and routine test on milk samples. Samples from
reactors are undergoing cultural examination.
Veterinary advice was that 4 of the reactors should be culled.
Slaughter of the 4, with compensation, has now been carried out and
further testing will be done on lymph nodes to check for _Brucella_.
Sampling of the remaining reactors, who are in isolation, has taken
place and the blood and milk samples are under investigation.
Defra is also tracing any movements off the farm in recent months.
However, it is understood that the farm has been relatively
self-contained with few movements off the farm apart from to
slaughter. Testing has been undertaken on 2 premises under the same
management. There have been no abortions reported from the farm and
no other clinical evidence that Brucellosis has been identified.
_Brucella_ cultures are relatively slow-growing, and results may not
be available for at least 2 weeks. There is a possibility that the
initial test results could be due to a cross-reaction to the test
rather than infection.
Notes for editors
----------------
1. Brucellosis of cattle is caused by infection with the bacterium
_Brucella abortus_, which can also cause a disease of humans known as
undulant fever. In cattle, it causes abortion or premature calving of
recently infected animals; the foetus, placenta and uterine fluid
contain large quantities of _Brucella abortus_ bacteria, which can
affect other cattle coming into contact with an infected animal
around the time of calving. The organism continues to be excreted in
the milk; in the past humans were frequently infected through
drinking unpasteurised milk.
2. The last case of Brucellosis was in 2004 in Cornwall. Details of
the last press release dated 20 Jul 2004 can be found at:
<http://www.defra.gov.uk/news/2004/040720d.htm>.
3. If slaughter is required, animals will be slaughtered under the
Brucellosis (England) Order 2000. Compensation is payable for
slaughter of reactors under the Brucellosis and Tuberculosis (England
and Wales) Compensation (Amendment) Order 1998 [NB the parent Order
is the Brucellosis and Tuberculosis (England and Wales - Compensation
Order 1978]. The maximum payable is calculated monthly based on the
average market price and for Mar 2005 is GBP 591 [USD 1105].
4. Article 10 of the Brucellosis (England) Order 2000 requires all
cattle farmers to report abortions and premature calving to the local
Animal Health office. Similar legislation is in place for Scotland
and Wales. Details of the disease [caused by infection with]
_Brucella abortus_ can be found on the Defra website at
<http://www.defra.gov.uk/news/2005//animalh/diseases/notifiable/disease/brucellosis.htm>.
5. A fact sheet for farmers, detailing what they should do in an
outbreak is also available on the Defra website at:
<http://www.defra.gov.uk/news/2005//animalh/diseases/notifiable/disease/brucellosis.htm>.
